1️⃣ Set Operations
Big Idea

Sometimes we combine results of multiple queries.

That is where set operations come in.

Think of math sets.

🔹 UNION

Combines results of two queries and removes duplicates.

Example

CSE students:

SELECT name FROM cse_students
UNION
SELECT name FROM ece_students;

If Akshay appears in both tables, UNION keeps only one.

Mental Model 🧠
UNION = merge + remove duplicates
UNION ALL

Keeps duplicates too.

SELECT name FROM cse_students
UNION ALL
SELECT name FROM ece_students;

Memory:

UNION ALL = keep all
Python Connection
set(list1).union(set(list2))
🔹 INTERSECT

Common rows in both queries.

SELECT name FROM cse_students
INTERSECT
SELECT name FROM ece_students;

Only common names.

Memory:

INTERSECT = overlap only
Python
set(a).intersection(set(b))
🔹 EXCEPT

Rows in first query but not second.

SELECT name FROM cse_students
EXCEPT
SELECT name FROM ece_students;

Memory:

EXCEPT = subtract set
Important Rule ⚠️

Queries combined with set operators should have:

✔ Same number of columns
✔ Compatible data types

Easy Summary
Operator	Meaning
UNION	combine unique rows
UNION ALL	combine all
INTERSECT	common rows
EXCEPT	first minus second
2️⃣ Join Interview Patterns

Now common interview tricks.

Pattern 1
Find unmatched rows

Students with no enrollments.

Use LEFT JOIN + NULL check.

SELECT s.name
FROM students s
LEFT JOIN enrollments e
ON s.id = e.student_id
WHERE e.student_id IS NULL;
Mental Model
LEFT JOIN keeps all students

NULL means no match

Classic interview problem.

Pattern 2
Find duplicate rows
SELECT email, COUNT(*)
FROM users
GROUP BY email
HAVING COUNT(*) > 1;

Very common.

Pattern 3
Second highest salary

Classic famous interview question.

SELECT MAX(salary)
FROM employees
WHERE salary <
(
 SELECT MAX(salary)
 FROM employees
);
Mental Model
Find highest

Then find highest below that
Pattern 4

Employees earning above department average.

SELECT e.name
FROM employees e
JOIN (
SELECT dept, AVG(salary) avg_sal
FROM employees
GROUP BY dept
) d
ON e.dept=d.dept
WHERE e.salary>d.avg_sal;

Advanced but common.

🔥 Placement Insight

Very common questions:

Q1 Difference UNION vs UNION ALL?

UNION removes duplicates.

UNION ALL keeps them.

Q2 How find records with no match?

LEFT JOIN + IS NULL

Q3 How find second highest salary?

Subquery (as above)

Quick Revision
UNION → merge

INTERSECT → common

EXCEPT → subtract

Interview Patterns:
No match → LEFT JOIN + NULL
Duplicates → GROUP BY HAVING
Second highest → subquery
